# Podman Core Guide: Concepts and Essential Command Cheat Sheet

Podman (Pod Manager) is an open-source, OCI (Open Container Initiative) compliant container engine. Adopted as the default containerization tool in Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL), it provides a drop-in replacement for Docker while delivering a more secure and lightweight architecture.

---

## 1. Key Features of Podman

* **Daemonless:** Unlike Docker, Podman does not rely on a central background daemon (`dockerd`). Containers launch as standard child processes, reducing resource overhead and eliminating a Single Point of Failure (SPOF).
* **Rootless:** A cornerstone for security. Standard, non-privileged users can seamlessly create, run, and manage containers without requiring `root` access, drastically minimizing the system's attack surface.
* **Native Pod Support:** Similar to Kubernetes, Podman allows you to group multiple containers into a single "Pod," enabling them to share network namespaces and local storage volumes.

---

## 2. Essential Commands Reference

Most core container mutations mirror standard docker CLI behaviors; simply replace `docker` with `podman`.

| Command | Description | Example |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `podman pull` | Download images from a remote registry | `podman pull nginx` |
| `podman images` | List cached images on the local storage | `podman images` |
| `podman run` | Provision and spin up a new container instance | `podman run -d --name web nginx` |
| `podman ps` | List active containers (Use `-a` for all states) | `podman ps -a` |
| `podman stop` | Gracefully halt a running container instance | `podman stop web` |
| `podman rm` | Evict a container (`-f` forces removal) | `podman rm -f web` |
| `podman rmi` | Permanently erase a local container image | `podman rmi nginx` |
| `podman logs` | Fetch runtime stdout/stderr container logs | `podman logs web` |
| `podman exec` | Execute an interactive process inside a container | `podman exec -it web bash` |

